{"id":"1812.03841","submitter":"Fabian Single","authors":"Fabian Single, Arnulf Latz, Birger Horstmann","title":"Identifying the Mechanism of Continued Growth of the Solid-Electrolyte\n  Interphase","comments":"4 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":"ChemSusChem 11 (2018) 1950-1955","doi":"10.1002/cssc.201800077","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.chem-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Continued growth of the solid electrolyte interphase (SEI) is the major\nreason for capacity fade in modern lithium-ion batteries. This growth is made\npossible by a yet unidentified transport mechanism that limits the passivating\nability of the SEI towards electrolyte reduction. We, for the first time,\ndifferentiate the proposed mechanisms by analyzing their dependence on the\nelectrode potential. Our calculations are compared to recent experimental\ncapacity fade data. We show that the potential dependence of SEI growth\nfacilitated by solvent diffusion, electron conduction, or electron tunneling\nqualitatively disagrees with the experimental observations. Only diffusion of\nLi-interstitials results in a potential dependence matching to the experiments.\nTherefore, we identify Li-interstitial diffusion as the cause of long-term SEI\ngrowth.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 10 Dec 2018 14:51:16 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 11 Dec 2018 08:54:57 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-12-12"}
